article.description: Betty Lennox scored 25 points, Lauren Jackson 23 and Iziane Castro Marques 22 to lead Seattle to two franchise scoring records and a league record in a win over Phoenix.
article.headline: Trio puts up 70  as Seattle sets scoring marks vs. Phoenix
article.linkText: Storm set scoring marks in win over Mercury
article.story:
SEATTLE -- Betty Lennox scored 25 points, Lauren Jackson 23 and Iziane Castro Marques 22 to lead the Seattle Storm to break two franchise scoring records as well as tie a league record in a 111-101 win over the Phoenix Mercury on Saturday night.

The Storm broke the team record of 100 points set in a win over Phoenix on May 23. Seattle tied a league record with 40 points in the first quarter when it led by 25 points. Detroit scored 40 against Phoenix on July 8.

"The first quarter was the best quarter we have ever played," Jackson said. "It was awesome. That won us the game."

Seattle also set a franchise record with 61 points in the first half, breaking the record of 56 set in 2003 against Los Angeles.

"Their philosophy is to outscore people so you just have to outscore them," Castro Marques said. "They don't focus as much on defense. If you have a good offensive team, you're going to get your buckets."

Seattle (14-15) snapped a three-game losing streak and stayed three games ahead of Los Angeles for the fourth and final playoff berth with five games left. The Storm won the season series against Phoenix 2-1.

Diana Taurasi scored 28 points and Cappie Pondexter had 24 for Phoenix (18-11), which dropped into a first-place tie with San Antonio in the Western Conference. The Mercury had won six consecutive games and four in a row on the road.

The Storm shot 76 percent (16-for-21) from the field in the opening quarter, including 6-for-8 on 3-pointers.

"They were just shooting the lights out," Phoenix coach Paul Westhead said. "It wasn't like we fell down or missed our coverage."

Castro Marques scored 15 in the first quarter when she made four 3-pointers. Lennox added 11 points and Jackson eight in the opening quarter to give the Storm a 40-17 lead.

"We were very focused," Castro Marques said. "We came out shooting the ball well, defended the fast break and defended the 3-point line. We did just about everything pretty much perfect."

The Storm tied a team record with 13 3-pointers. Castro Marques made five. Sue Bird and Katie Gearlds each made three 3-pointers.

Phoenix, which has clinched a playoff berth, cut the lead to seven points late in the fourth quarter.

"We needed a win for sure," Seattle coach Anne Donovan said. "We needed to prove to ourselves that we can compete and get on the positive side of some of these Western opponents."

Seattle is 2-8 against the top three Western Conference teams, with both wins against Phoenix. Sacramento and San Antonio swept the season series against the Storm.

Donovan earned her 135th career WNBA victory, second to Van Chancellor with 211.

Jackson, who shot 10-for-11 from the free-throw line and had 12 rebounds, left Friday's game at Sacramento in the second quarter with a groin injury. She had eight points in the loss.

Jackson has a league-leading 16 double-doubles.
